WEBVTT

00:00:12.060 --> 00:00:14.760
Just carbonizing your app,
although that will get you on 10,

00:00:14.760 --> 00:00:18.330
isn't really going to necessarily
deliver the full user experience that

00:00:18.330 --> 00:00:21.750
users are going to come to expect when
they start using the OS in general.

00:00:21.750 --> 00:00:24.850
They're going to be looking for
things like sheets and different

00:00:25.090 --> 00:00:26.830
behaviors that Aqua presents.

00:00:26.870 --> 00:00:30.460
So this session helps you understand
what that design philosophy

00:00:30.460 --> 00:00:33.900
was behind Aqua so that as you
start to bring your app to 10,

00:00:33.900 --> 00:00:38.420
you can start to design your interface
and your user experience around that.

00:00:38.570 --> 00:00:42.690
So to talk about the design of Aqua,
I'd like to introduce It's Don Lindsey,

00:00:42.710 --> 00:00:45.400
the head of the human
interface team here at Apple.

00:00:50.600 --> 00:00:53.910
Thanks John.

00:00:54.170 --> 00:00:56.160
Okay, Aqua Overview.

00:00:56.160 --> 00:00:58.390
I'm going to talk about Aqua today.

00:00:58.420 --> 00:01:01.630
I'm not going to talk about architecture,
I'm not going to talk

00:01:01.690 --> 00:01:05.110
about frameworks or APIs.

00:01:05.260 --> 00:01:09.200
In fact, I promise I won't show any
more slides like this at all.

00:01:09.200 --> 00:01:11.070
This is the only one.

00:01:12.160 --> 00:01:16.660
What I do want to talk
about is what is Aqua?

00:01:16.770 --> 00:01:18.800
Steve, when he introduced it,
said it is the user

00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:21.210
interface of Mac OS X.

00:01:21.350 --> 00:01:23.700
and I want to expand on that
a little bit because I think

00:01:23.800 --> 00:01:25.740
there are some misconceptions.

00:01:25.790 --> 00:01:27.640
I also want to talk about
what is new in Aqua.

00:01:27.670 --> 00:01:29.100
What have we introduced?

00:01:29.130 --> 00:01:33.860
Many of you today probably already
have applications shipping on Mac OS 9.

00:01:33.890 --> 00:01:36.920
I want to point out those things
which are a little bit new in

00:01:36.920 --> 00:01:39.410
Aqua that you should be aware of.

00:01:39.540 --> 00:01:42.000
I also want to talk about what
we've changed since Macworld.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:45.100
We introduced this thing
almost six months ago now,

00:01:45.190 --> 00:01:47.830
and we haven't just been sitting back.

00:01:47.930 --> 00:01:49.250
We've been pretty busy.

00:01:49.270 --> 00:01:52.570
Steve mentioned we've been listening
to the feedback we got from you having

00:01:52.570 --> 00:01:56.040
played with Developer Preview 3,
and we're making some changes.

00:01:56.130 --> 00:01:57.820
We're making improvements.

00:01:57.820 --> 00:02:00.530
And finally, at the very end,
I'm going to bring John back on stage,

00:02:00.530 --> 00:02:04.350
who's going to list for you
all of the sessions that are

00:02:04.590 --> 00:02:06.370
related to adopting Aqua.

00:02:06.580 --> 00:02:08.440
So let's get started.

00:02:08.460 --> 00:02:10.180
What is Aqua?

00:02:10.200 --> 00:02:13.600
Well, judging by the email I get
and what I read online,

00:02:13.600 --> 00:02:17.180
I'm beginning to think that
Aqua is a kaleidoscope scheme.

00:02:17.320 --> 00:02:21.060
Or it's a SoundJam skin,
or it's one of those things.

00:02:21.300 --> 00:02:28.390
Aqua is the user interface for Mac OS X.

00:02:29.440 --> 00:02:31.720
Okay, what does that mean?

00:02:31.750 --> 00:02:34.560
What do we say when we
say it's a user interface?

00:02:34.580 --> 00:02:37.680
Well, obviously, it is an appearance,
yes.

00:02:37.720 --> 00:02:39.140
But it's also a set of behaviors.

00:02:39.220 --> 00:02:42.190
It's how things respond
when you select them.

00:02:42.950 --> 00:02:46.560
It's also a set of features that we
provide that are available to you,

00:02:46.640 --> 00:02:49.940
things like our Save panel,
our Print panel,

00:02:50.000 --> 00:02:55.040
that you can use and adopt to
deliver Aqua in your applications.

00:02:55.060 --> 00:02:57.060
It's also a collection of
applications that we ship,

00:02:57.160 --> 00:02:59.940
like the Finder and various
utilities that we ship.

00:03:00.100 --> 00:03:03.710
Collectively, this describes the user
experience of Mac OS X.

00:03:03.780 --> 00:03:07.500
So again,
user experience is not just appearance,

00:03:07.520 --> 00:03:10.050
but it is behaviors,
and it is a set of features

00:03:10.100 --> 00:03:11.760
that you can adopt.

00:03:12.160 --> 00:03:16.840
Now what you may find surprising
is that from my standpoint,

00:03:16.850 --> 00:03:19.390
you're also contributing to Aqua.

00:03:20.440 --> 00:03:24.880
If you carbonize your app and you
deliver it on Mac OS X and you do

00:03:25.010 --> 00:03:28.940
a really poor job of adopting Aqua,
then you're weakening the

00:03:28.940 --> 00:03:30.800
user experience of Mac OS X.

00:03:30.800 --> 00:03:32.720
People are going to run it and
they're going to be confused.

00:03:32.760 --> 00:03:36.120
For years and years,
we have been touting consistency as

00:03:36.120 --> 00:03:40.300
one of the most important aspects
of the Macintosh user experience.

00:03:41.840 --> 00:03:45.170
So it's important for me,
it's important for Apple,

00:03:45.170 --> 00:03:48.560
that you understand what we're
trying to achieve with Aqua.

00:03:48.560 --> 00:03:49.740
So that's what I want to talk about.

00:03:52.470 --> 00:03:55.160
When we started Aqua,
almost two years ago,

00:03:55.160 --> 00:03:58.790
we started thinking about this new
user experience we wanted to deliver.

00:03:58.880 --> 00:04:03.490
We've stated a number of goals,
things we wanted Aqua to achieve.

00:04:03.570 --> 00:04:07.410
The very first of which was that
Aqua had to deliver the best

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:12.000
user experience of any commercial
operating system on the market,

00:04:12.000 --> 00:04:13.260
unsurpassed.

00:04:14.570 --> 00:04:18.580
Somewhat of a lofty goal,
but we're up to the task.

00:04:18.580 --> 00:04:19.740
It had to be fun.

00:04:19.740 --> 00:04:22.420
We wanted to bring back
joy of use to computers.

00:04:22.420 --> 00:04:27.630
Things have gotten so complex that
we had to find ways to address this.

00:04:27.760 --> 00:04:29.790
We had to find ways to make it simpler.

00:04:32.010 --> 00:04:36.940
Mac OS has a very long tradition
of setting the standard for

00:04:36.940 --> 00:04:39.320
ease of use in our industry.

00:04:39.560 --> 00:04:42.400
and with Aqua,
we wanted to build on that.

00:04:42.400 --> 00:04:45.740
We didn't want to just throw
that away and start again.

00:04:45.770 --> 00:04:49.080
We know what the
strengths of Mac OS 9 are.

00:04:49.110 --> 00:04:51.800
We had full intentions
of using them in Aqua,

00:04:51.830 --> 00:04:54.850
but we also saw opportunities
to improve upon that.

00:04:56.100 --> 00:05:20.500
[Transcript missing]

00:05:21.500 --> 00:05:25.700
Finally,
we wanted Aqua to be recognizable.

00:05:25.700 --> 00:05:28.400
We wanted it to have a strong identity.

00:05:28.400 --> 00:05:31.400
Apple is about leadership
and product design.

00:05:31.400 --> 00:05:35.040
And we've been hugely successful with
our hardware in the last two years.

00:05:35.040 --> 00:05:37.650
And now with Aqua,
we want to do the same with our software.

00:05:40.460 --> 00:05:42.780
So what is new?

00:05:42.860 --> 00:05:44.600
You have a Mac OS 9 app.

00:05:44.730 --> 00:05:46.220
You're carbonizing it.

00:05:46.260 --> 00:05:48.260
Things that you should be aware of.

00:05:48.310 --> 00:05:50.080
So first of all, appearance.

00:05:50.100 --> 00:05:51.720
Appearance is new in Aqua.

00:05:51.740 --> 00:05:54.220
And there is only one appearance in Aqua.

00:05:55.470 --> 00:05:56.880
This is it.

00:05:57.030 --> 00:06:02.750
This is the very first slide that
was publicly shown at Macworld.

00:06:03.100 --> 00:06:06.290
Revealing the user interface
or the appearance of Aqua.

00:06:06.470 --> 00:06:10.150
Today I actually considered giving
slides of each and every control

00:06:10.150 --> 00:06:13.460
and talking about them all,
but then I said, I don't have to do that.

00:06:13.460 --> 00:06:14.470
I could just show this.

00:06:14.510 --> 00:06:19.120
This really captures all of what
the appearance is trying to achieve.

00:06:21.170 --> 00:06:26.890
This button speaks to what the
design language of Aqua is.

00:06:27.080 --> 00:06:34.090
It is light, it is clear, it is fresh,
it is clean, it is crisp, it is subtle.

00:06:34.910 --> 00:06:39.490
Where platinum relies on black
lines and gray lines to define

00:06:39.490 --> 00:06:44.500
frames of windows and the shapes of
buttons and the volume of a button,

00:06:44.500 --> 00:06:48.670
Aqua uses much more subtle visual cues.

00:06:48.670 --> 00:06:51.080
We're using shadow, we're using light,
we're using color, we're using color.

00:06:51.100 --> 00:06:53.500
We're using very subtle tonal gradations.

00:06:53.610 --> 00:06:56.250
We can do this because we've got quartz.

00:06:56.340 --> 00:06:59.430
We've got this great graphics
engine underneath that allows us to

00:06:59.510 --> 00:07:01.300
draw these to the screen very fast.

00:07:05.070 --> 00:07:08.930
So rather than linger on each and every
control and walk you through all those,

00:07:08.930 --> 00:07:12.670
I thought I'd rather look at more
interesting parts of the appearance.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:16.200
Other areas which are related to
appearance but are not directly

00:07:16.200 --> 00:07:18.140
related to how a control looks.

00:07:18.140 --> 00:07:20.160
And one of those is translucency.

00:07:20.160 --> 00:07:24.470
Now,
we played around a lot with translucency.

00:07:24.490 --> 00:07:28.440
We tried translucent windows and
we tried all sorts of controls

00:07:28.440 --> 00:07:30.810
that were fading in and fading out.

00:07:30.860 --> 00:07:34.570
And what we discovered in all
of that exploration was that

00:07:34.570 --> 00:07:36.640
translucency is a novelty.

00:07:36.640 --> 00:07:39.980
That you could very quickly tire of this.

00:07:41.180 --> 00:07:47.190
So our conclusion was that translucency
only added value if it had meaning.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:51.140
This is very important because
this comes up again in something

00:07:51.140 --> 00:07:52.800
else I'm going to talk to.

00:07:52.860 --> 00:07:58.100
We chose to use translucency
on those controls which are

00:07:58.100 --> 00:07:59.830
of more transient nature.

00:07:59.930 --> 00:08:02.400
So for example, I can see here a menu.

00:08:02.910 --> 00:08:04.530
Um, menus come and go.

00:08:04.660 --> 00:08:06.000
They only exist for a very short time.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:08.440
You make a selection and it disappears.

00:08:08.590 --> 00:08:12.590
Translucency is nice because it
reinforces that a menu is very light.

00:08:13.630 --> 00:08:17.110
Likewise,
we use translucency in our sheets.

00:08:17.150 --> 00:08:20.590
Sheets, again,
typically only exist for a short time.

00:08:20.620 --> 00:08:23.070
They're usually not presented
for long periods of time.

00:08:23.080 --> 00:08:26.380
Saving a document, printing a document,
or an alert, for example.

00:08:26.380 --> 00:08:27.960
Sheets come and go.

00:08:27.960 --> 00:08:29.360
Therefore, translucency was perfect.

00:08:29.400 --> 00:08:32.280
Translucency was perfect for
sheets as well because sheets are

00:08:32.340 --> 00:08:33.830
tied to their parent document.

00:08:33.830 --> 00:08:36.910
Of course, they obscure some of the
content that's underneath.

00:08:36.910 --> 00:08:40.420
So using translucency allowed you to
reveal just enough that was underneath

00:08:40.420 --> 00:08:42.460
to remind you what that document was.

00:08:45.020 --> 00:08:48.030
Like translucency,
we had the opportunity to

00:08:48.040 --> 00:08:50.400
use a lot of color in Aqua.

00:08:50.420 --> 00:08:52.540
And we tried a lot of colors.

00:08:52.540 --> 00:08:54.700
We played around with color for
the better part of the last year,

00:08:54.700 --> 00:08:58.990
trying to find what kinds of colors,
what palette to use,

00:08:58.990 --> 00:09:02.040
what would be our theme of our color.

00:09:02.190 --> 00:09:07.370
But like translucency,
we came to the conclusion that color

00:09:07.430 --> 00:09:10.080
was useful only again if it had

00:09:10.640 --> 00:09:12.430
And in this example,
in this dialogue where you

00:09:12.430 --> 00:09:17.540
see an assortment of controls,
color says, I am the selected control.

00:09:17.550 --> 00:09:19.750
I am the one you've chosen.

00:09:20.250 --> 00:09:23.440
In the tab, for example,
that is the selected tab.

00:09:23.450 --> 00:09:27.820
Radio buttons, check boxes,
and even the pop-up says that I am

00:09:27.820 --> 00:09:29.530
the current choice that you have.

00:09:29.530 --> 00:09:34.980
That's the meaning of color and how
we've chosen to color our controls.

00:09:35.940 --> 00:09:40.600
In the windows,
we actually have used three colors.

00:09:40.600 --> 00:09:42.520
We have three controls in our title bar.

00:09:42.520 --> 00:09:44.030
We've carried forward from Mac OS 9.

00:09:44.040 --> 00:09:44.990
We have the close box.

00:09:45.040 --> 00:09:47.300
We have the minimize control.

00:09:47.300 --> 00:09:48.620
And we have the zoom control.

00:09:48.620 --> 00:09:50.780
And they have very
different functionality.

00:09:50.800 --> 00:09:53.270
So we decided, first,
we knew we wanted to group them.

00:09:53.270 --> 00:09:57.100
Secondly,
we had to distinguish them somehow.

00:09:57.170 --> 00:09:59.950
So we chose to go with three colors.

00:09:59.950 --> 00:10:03.310
It's somewhat of a playful decision,
but I think it's quite effective.

00:10:05.270 --> 00:10:09.280
One interesting aspect of the appearance,
it's related to appearance,

00:10:09.280 --> 00:10:11.390
but it's not specifically
how something is rendered,

00:10:11.460 --> 00:10:15.750
but rather our approach to how
we've chosen to organize the screen.

00:10:16.350 --> 00:10:18.220
These three examples,
actually including the doc,

00:10:18.370 --> 00:10:23.380
four examples, show how we've decided to
take a more center justified,

00:10:23.440 --> 00:10:26.440
actually that's not even correct,
I would say center biased

00:10:26.440 --> 00:10:29.800
approach to organizing the screen.

00:10:29.800 --> 00:10:32.640
The sheet is in the middle of the window.

00:10:32.640 --> 00:10:36.760
The controls in the dialogue
have a more central alignment,

00:10:36.760 --> 00:10:39.320
central biased alignment to them.

00:10:39.320 --> 00:10:41.420
The tabs are in the middle of the window.

00:10:41.420 --> 00:10:45.070
Even in the QuickTime player,
the play control, the most important

00:10:45.170 --> 00:10:48.200
control on that window,
smack in the middle.

00:10:48.260 --> 00:10:49.750
Other controls are organized around that.

00:10:51.430 --> 00:10:52.660
The dock is centered.

00:10:52.660 --> 00:10:54.570
It remains centered,
regardless of how many

00:10:54.570 --> 00:10:55.670
things you add or remove.

00:10:55.690 --> 00:11:00.040
It always stays center
aligned on the screen.

00:11:00.060 --> 00:11:01.680
Even the Apple logo you
see in the menu bar,

00:11:01.680 --> 00:11:03.720
even that center of the screen.

00:11:03.790 --> 00:11:06.330
This is an important
change because platinum was

00:11:06.500 --> 00:11:08.110
typically more left justified.

00:11:08.110 --> 00:11:09.980
We've changed it a little bit.

00:11:09.980 --> 00:11:12.670
This is primarily an aesthetic decision.

00:11:12.840 --> 00:11:16.410
It's about achieving
balance and symmetry.

00:11:16.470 --> 00:11:19.770
We think it makes for
a much cleaner design.

00:11:21.390 --> 00:11:25.400
So beyond appearance,
we've added a few new behaviors.

00:11:25.500 --> 00:11:27.520
We've changed some behaviors.

00:11:27.550 --> 00:11:31.800
Mac OS, when it was first introduced,
and what it popularized in

00:11:31.830 --> 00:11:35.280
graphical user interfaces,
were two key tenets.

00:11:35.300 --> 00:11:38.250
One, direct manipulation.

00:11:39.120 --> 00:11:41.240
When you grab something on
the screen and moved it,

00:11:41.240 --> 00:11:42.350
you were moving that object.

00:11:42.460 --> 00:11:44.950
You were operating on that object.

00:11:45.200 --> 00:11:50.660
And yet for 15 years we've been dragging
gray rectangles around the screen.

00:11:51.110 --> 00:11:53.320
Aqua changes that.

00:11:53.340 --> 00:11:54.380
We have live dragging.

00:11:54.380 --> 00:11:55.570
We have live resizing.

00:11:55.630 --> 00:11:56.350
Live scrolling.

00:11:56.410 --> 00:11:57.070
Everything is live.

00:11:57.200 --> 00:12:03.760
We've taken direct manipulation
all the way to its conclusion.

00:12:06.550 --> 00:12:09.550
The other thing that was about
Mac OS that was respected was the

00:12:09.640 --> 00:12:10.840
fact that it provided feedback.

00:12:10.900 --> 00:12:13.610
It told the user at any time,
"This is what you are doing.

00:12:13.790 --> 00:12:18.080
This is the status of the task
that you're trying to accomplish."

00:12:18.470 --> 00:12:23.450
In Aqua, again in part thanks to Quartz,
we have the ability to do more

00:12:23.450 --> 00:12:26.400
interesting animations and transitions.

00:12:26.570 --> 00:12:29.250
We're able to say,
you saw this morning in the keynote,

00:12:29.260 --> 00:12:32.300
a minimized window,
how it animates into the dock.

00:12:32.300 --> 00:12:33.440
We're able to achieve that.

00:12:33.510 --> 00:12:36.640
We're able to illustrate to you
where this window is going to.

00:12:36.640 --> 00:12:38.120
It's really quite successful.

00:12:38.120 --> 00:12:42.040
So in addition to behaviors,

00:12:43.010 --> 00:12:45.000
We looked at introducing
a few new features,

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:46.900
user interface features.

00:12:46.930 --> 00:12:51.980
Now these are things that are available
in our frameworks in Carbon and

00:12:51.980 --> 00:12:54.100
Cocoa that you can take advantage of.

00:12:54.100 --> 00:12:58.760
And we've designed them to solve specific
problems that we recognize exist today,

00:12:59.010 --> 00:13:02.070
not just in Mac OS 9,
but in all operating systems.

00:13:03.680 --> 00:13:10.170
When Mac OS was originally built,
designed and built, you could only open

00:13:10.170 --> 00:13:13.170
one document at a time.

00:13:14.380 --> 00:13:17.800
You can only run one
application at a time.

00:13:17.800 --> 00:13:19.990
Things have changed a
little bit since then.

00:13:20.080 --> 00:13:24.400
It's not uncommon today to have for
an intermediate or an expert user to

00:13:24.400 --> 00:13:27.300
have five to ten applications running.

00:13:27.340 --> 00:13:30.690
Fifteen to twenty windows
open on the screen.

00:13:30.730 --> 00:13:32.730
This is chaos.

00:13:33.590 --> 00:13:38.460
So we've looked for ways to
help people focus on what

00:13:38.520 --> 00:13:40.620
they're trying to accomplish.

00:13:40.640 --> 00:13:44.190
We look for opportunities to
introduce new features to reduce

00:13:44.190 --> 00:13:45.730
the modality in the system.

00:13:45.730 --> 00:13:50.090
Areas or at times during a
task where you are blocked,

00:13:50.090 --> 00:13:52.120
we try to reduce that.

00:13:52.200 --> 00:13:55.200
I'll explain a little bit more of
that when we get to that feature.

00:13:55.200 --> 00:13:56.700
And finally,
we look for ways to help people

00:13:56.700 --> 00:14:00.840
manage all this clutter on the screen,
all these windows.

00:14:00.870 --> 00:14:03.140
So let's look at a few of these features.

00:14:03.910 --> 00:14:05.430
window layering.

00:14:05.850 --> 00:14:09.990
Now, if you're familiar with Mac OS,
you know that if I have, say,

00:14:10.120 --> 00:14:13.200
five windows open in a word processor,

00:14:13.890 --> 00:14:17.290
and I just want to one
of those to work on.

00:14:17.290 --> 00:14:21.440
If I select it,
all five windows come to the front.

00:14:21.440 --> 00:14:22.230
It's not what I wanted.

00:14:22.250 --> 00:14:24.230
I just wanted that one.

00:14:26.250 --> 00:14:29.170
It's not,
it reinforces the fact that we are,

00:14:29.170 --> 00:14:33.820
we remain in Mac OS 9 very
conscious of applications and the

00:14:33.820 --> 00:14:36.180
layering between applications.

00:14:36.990 --> 00:14:38.500
So with Aqua, we wanted to change that.

00:14:38.520 --> 00:14:41.660
We wanted to move more towards
focusing on the content,

00:14:41.660 --> 00:14:44.190
on the document the person's working on.

00:14:45.490 --> 00:14:46.980
So we've changed the way windows layer.

00:14:47.070 --> 00:14:52.180
We now allow full interleaving
of windows between applications.

00:14:53.600 --> 00:14:57.480
So when I've got five word processing
documents open and I just want to

00:14:57.480 --> 00:15:02.680
work on one and I at the same time
perhaps have ten illustrations open

00:15:02.770 --> 00:15:07.630
and say my task is to copy one of the
illustrations into my word processor,

00:15:07.630 --> 00:15:10.510
I don't need to bring all
five illustrations forward.

00:15:10.630 --> 00:15:12.000
I just bring the one I want.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:15.900
And I put it into the word
processing document I want.

00:15:15.980 --> 00:15:19.220
We think this is a much
more natural way to work.

00:15:20.280 --> 00:15:23.750
and it really facilitates moving
content between individual documents

00:15:23.760 --> 00:15:30.950
without having to be conscious about
applications coming forward and receding.

